{"parse":{"title":"Horizontal effect","pageid":15646576,"revid":684706380,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In law, <b>horizontal effect</b> refers to the ability of legal requirements meant to apply only to public bodies to affect private rights. It arises where a court dealing with a legal dispute between purely private entities interprets a legal provision to be consistent with certain legal norms in such a way as to affect the legal rights and obligations of the parties before it.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Examples\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Examples</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Further_reading_and_external_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Further reading and external links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Examples\">Examples</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Horizontal_effect&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Examples\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In <a href=\"/wiki/European_Union_law\" title=\"European Union law\">European Union law</a> under the doctrine of <a href=\"/wiki/Direct_effect\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Direct effect\">direct effect</a>, national courts are under a legal duty to interpret national laws to be consistent with EU laws which the member state concerned has either not implemented or not implemented correctly. The ability of such interpretations to affect the legal rights and duties of purely private entities is called horizontal direct effect. Normally, direct effect is only vertical, in that it is meant to apply to the state and its emanations (i.e., to public sector employers).\n</p><p>In the <a href=\"/wiki/United_Kingdom\" title=\"United Kingdom\">United Kingdom</a>, in Campbell v Mirror Group Newspapers,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> the House of Lords found that while the <a href=\"/wiki/Human_Rights_Act_1998\" title=\"Human Rights Act 1998\">Human Rights Act 1998</a> cannot create new causes of action between individuals, \"if there is a relevant cause of action, the court as a public authority must act compatibly with both parties' Convention rights.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Horizontal_effect&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Human_Rights_Act_1998\" title=\"Human Rights Act 1998\">Human Rights Act 1998</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Direct_effect\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Direct effect\">Direct effect</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Vertical_effect\" title=\"Vertical effect\">Vertical effect</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Horizontal_effect&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">[2004] UKHL 22</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">per Baroness Hale.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading_and_external_links\">Further reading and external links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Horizontal_effect&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading and external links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>J. Morgan, \u2018Privacy in the House of Lords, Again\u2019 (2004) 120 Law Quarterly Review 563.</li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.yourrights.org.uk/vas/the-human-rights-act/private-parties-and-the-hra.doc\">An explanation of the term from yourrights.org</a></li></ul>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Scale_of_justice_2.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Scale_of_justice_2.svg/22px-Scale_of_justice_2.svg.png\" width=\"22\" height=\"22\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Scale_of_justice_2.svg/33px-Scale_of_justice_2.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Scale_of_justice_2.svg/44px-Scale_of_justice_2.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"204\" data-file-height=\"208\" /></a></td><td><i>This <a href=\"/wiki/Law\" title=\"Law\">law</a>-related article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help 